Comment: Here playing black in a blitz game. I'm playing the sicilian defense, since I don't like that much to defend with e5. Sometime I play the Caro-Kann, but I'm not that much experimented with the advance variation that I see often these days.

The immediate e5 give the possibility to develop the bishop for castling and reduce the threat of the knight. White have to chose: Nf3 or Nb3. Ne2 is possible but white will need to move the knight again later to be able to develop the bishop.

For right now the knight look to be blocked by the pawns, but he can be very useful later in the game.

?! b5 is a normal idea of the sicilian, but I think finally Nc6 would have been a better continuation. At this point, I was more experimenting than anything since I don't really know all the variations.

Well I was expecting exd5, I was quite shocked by the position. The queen threats my rook and there is no way I can protect it. My only solution at this point was to try to trap the queen in the corner.
Qc7 was essential to be able to do Bb7 and this way I was able to threat c2 too ,so it could be useful later in the game.
?! Well I'm still not sure after all that it was a good move. With the accurate defense, I don't see a way for the queen to escape or to gain a big advantage.
! Nc6 blocks the way for the queen to escape and the queen can't go to a7.
Well nice try at this point, at least he gains a free pawn.
After the exchange, white still have 2 pt more than I have, but with this kind of position, I still prefer my queen to my 2 rooks.
